UV–Vis absorption and emission spectra of the as synthesized GQDs are shown in Fig. 2
                        A. The ground-state absorption characteristics of GQDs show a broad peak observed around 300–350 nm which is attributed to the n-π* transition of the CO bonds of the surface carboxylic groups of GQDs [20,21]. The GQDs used in this work displayed maximum emission at about 445 nm upon excitation at 340 nm. The fluorescence quantum yield (Φ
                           F
                        ) and lifetime (τ
                           F
                        ) were measured to be 0.31 and 5.7 (ns), respectively (Table S1).

The fluorescence of GQDs upon conjugation to CoPc resulted in a fluorescence “turn OFF” process as discussed above; Fig. 6. Conversely, the fluorescence was restored upon interaction with CN− as graphically depicted in (Fig. 7
                        A and Scheme 2
                        ).
